    "short_descriptor": "Late-20th and 21st-century American style emphasizing clean lines and mixed materials.",
    "background_prose": "Contemporary architecture in residential terms refers to the broader late-20th-century and 21st-century movement away from traditional historical styles toward clean geometric lines, asymmetric massing, oversized windows, and mixed materials. Unlike modern (which strictly refers to early-to-mid-20th-century Bauhaus and International Style), contemporary is the current-decade interpretation and continues to evolve. Key features include smooth stucco or cedar siding, oversized rectangular windows, flat-fronted facades with offset masses, and minimalist xeriscape front yards.",
