  "consider": {
    "kicker": "Things to consider · before you commit",
    "title_html": "Three things <em>most</em> homeowners forget.",
    "items": [
      {
        "number": "01.",
        "heading": "Contemporary reads cleanest with a flat or single-plane low-pitch roof.",
        "body": "Contemporary reads cleanest with a flat or single-plane low-pitch roof. Asphalt shingle on a contemporary build requires a deliberately dark single-tone color (true black, dark charcoal) -- multi-tone weathered-wood reads as architecturally inconsistent on this style. If your contemporary build has a steep gabled roof, the architecture is leaning toward modern farmhouse or transitional, not pure contemporary."
      },
      {
        "number": "02.",
        "heading": "Black roof + Florida sun = attic temperature delta.",
        "body": "A black asphalt roof can raise attic temperatures by 5 to 10 degrees Fahrenheit at peak Florida summer compared to a light-gray or weathered-wood roof. Proper soffit-to-ridge attic ventilation and a radiant barrier under the decking close most of the gap and keep monthly cooling-cost impact under 20 dollars in typical Florida homes."
      },
      {
        "number": "03.",
        "heading": "Install quality matters more than SKU.",
        "body": "All seven recommended SKUs hit Class A fire and 110-150 mph wind ratings. The bigger variable on a contemporary elevation is install quality: ridge-line straightness, valley flashing, starter strip alignment. Insist on a Master Elite or equivalent certified contractor and a written workmanship warranty separate from the manufacturer's material warranty."
      }
