  "faq_items": [
    {
      "q": "How is contemporary different from modern?",
      "a": "Modern in architecture refers specifically to the early-to-mid-20th-century Bauhaus and International Style movements -- think Frank Lloyd Wright, Mies van der Rohe. Contemporary is the current-decade interpretation: looser definitions, more material mixing, more regional adaptation. In casual usage they overlap, but architects distinguish them."
    },
    {
      "q": "What asphalt shingle color suits contemporary?",
      "a": "True black or deep charcoal in a single-tone (non-multi-tone) blend. Avoid weathered-wood, warm brown, and any 'natural' multi-tone product. Contemporary architecture wants the roof to read as one decided color from any angle."
    },
    {
      "q": "Will the black roof fade in Florida sun?",
      "a": "Modern asphalt shingles use ceramic-coated granules engineered to hold color for 25 plus years. Expect a subtle shift toward a slightly warmer dark gray over the first 5 years, then stability. Premium SKUs carry 25 to 50-year fade warranties. Source: NRCA Asphalt Shingle Manual."
    },
    {
      "q": "Does black roof affect home insurance in Florida?",
      "a": "Not because of color. Insurance underwriting cares about wind rating, hail rating, and the roof's age. All recommended SKUs on this page are 130 mph wind and Class A fire. Some Florida insurers offer a small discount for impact-rated (Class 3 or 4) variants."
    },
    {
